Introduction¶

In this project I will be working as a data scientist in a hospital and will be using Binary Classification Task Using Testlin Machine. For my project I will be using AI predictive Models to compare their performance against the Testlin Machine.¶

Business Question¶

Are patients at high risk of stroke based on their data provided in the hospital?¶

About the dataset¶

The dataset can be accessed from the following link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/fedesoriano/stroke-prediction-dataset. This dataset also contains 3 bianry columns which makes it better for the project.¶

Storke dataset is used in this project is gathered from Kaggle, its linked with the chances of stroke in patients. The dataset has non numerical columns like gender, heart diseases, martial status, work, residence, smoking status and numerical columns like id, age, hypertension, heart disease, glucose level, bmi and stroke.¶

Column Description¶

1. id: Unique identifier given to each patient at the hospital¶

2. gender: the gender of the patient¶

3. age: Age of different patients at the hospital¶

4. hypertension: denotes if a patient has high blood pressure or not (0: no, 1: yes)¶

5. heart_diesase: denotes if a patient ever had heart disease or not (0: no, 1: yes)¶

6. ever_married: martial status of a patient¶

7. work_type: Description of patients work status¶

8. Residence_type: Describes the type of neighbourhood the patient lives in¶

9. avg_glucose_level: Sugar concentration in a patients body¶

10. bmi: indicates the body mass index of a patient (a person's weight divided by their height)¶

11. smoking_status: describes if a person has ever smoked or not¶

12. stoke: defines if a person ever had a stroke before (0: no, 1: yes)¶

EDA and Data Preprocessing¶

EDA (Exploratory Data Analysis) is the process where the dataset is cleaned by handling the null, missing and duplicate values. The quality of the dataset will be insured for further analysis.¶

Insights from the steps done for EDA are:¶

1. Data Cleaning: While handling the missing values in the columns, I found that column BMI has some NaN values and replacing those values with the average values from the column.¶

2. Duplicates: Checking if the id's are different for all patients so that there wont be any duplicates during future use.¶

3. Categorical datas: Before Converting Categorical Data into Numerical Data I checked the columns with categorical data and the number of catergorical values in those columns.¶

Findings¶

After cleaning EDA process I realized that the stroke dataset had NaN values in bmi column and I adjusted that by replacing the NaN values with the average values in column. There are no duplicated values in my dataset. However, there are some categorical dataset that needs to be changed to numerical columns and some columns needs to be binarized which will be done in the Feature Engineering part.¶

I used Matplot library and Sea born and made pie chart to first find the distribution of patients who has stroke and later I also implemented KDE (Kernal Density Estimation) to figure out the distribution of the of the numerical columns and histograms to show the distribution of stroke based on how categorical datasets affected the stoke.¶

Findings:¶

- For the distribution of Stroke which is also the traget of the analysis we found that the patients who had stroke previously are relatively lesser than the patients who never had it.¶

Result: Patients who had stroke previously (Stroke): 4.9%¶

Patients who never had a stroke previously (No Stroke): 95.1%¶

- Based on the Statistical analysis the analysis tells that patients average age is 43-44 years and they have lesser chances of having hypertension and heart diseases. However, the avegrage glucose level in patients are pretty high and bmi is also pretty high.¶

- In the KDE analysis the age is distributed normally however we can see frequency being high after the age of 40. even though there is a down frequency after the age of 60, it again rises at 80. For average glucose level and the BMI, both are skewed towards the left.¶

- Based on Categorical Columns the trend with people getting storke work type and marital status is higher compared to the other columns. Females are a little more prone to stroke then men and people living in urban places are more prone to stroke then people living in rural places.¶

Feature Engineering¶

For the Feature Engineering step the approches taken into consideration are One hot encoding categorical data¶

One Hot Encoding: One hot encoding is a process to transform categorical data into numerical data. It is a feature in scikit learn. It basically creates a binary column for each category which was originally a string.¶

Correlation Matrix: The corrleation matrix helps us to know which features are most to least correlated with the target which is stroke for this case. So age has a positive correlation where as work type children has a negative correlation with stroke¶

# Implementing Generic Algorithm

# fitness function
def fitness_function(features, X, y):

    selected_features = X[:, features]
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(selected_features, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
    X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)
    tm = MultiClassTsetlinMachine(number_of_clauses=250, T=100, s=8.0)
    tm.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=6)
    y_pred = tm.predict(X_test)
    fitness_score = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')
    return fitness_score

# Genetic Algorithm

def GA(X, y, population_size=20, num_generations=100, mutation_rate=0.15, feature_number=10, early_stopping_generations=20):
    X, y = check_X_y(X, y, accept_sparse=False, force_all_finite=False)
    random_state = check_random_state(None)
    
    population = [random.sample(range(X.shape[1]), feature_number) for _ in range(population_size)]
    best_fitness = 0
    
    generations_without_improvement = 0
    for generation in range(num_generations):
        scores = [fitness_function(features, X, y) for features in population]
        fitness_scores = [score for score in scores]
        current_best_fitness = max(fitness_scores)
        
        if current_best_fitness > best_fitness:
            best_fitness = current_best_fitness
            generations_without_improvement = 0
            
        else:
            generations_without_improvement += 1
            
        if generations_without_improvement >= early_stopping_generations:
            print("Early stopping: No improvement in fitness for the last {} generations.".format(early_stopping_generations))
            break
        num_parents = int(population_size / 2)
        parents = np.argsort(fitness_scores)[-num_parents:].tolist()
        new_population = []
        
        while len(new_population) < population_size:
            parent1, parent2 = random.sample(parents, 2)
            crossover_point = random.randint(1, feature_number - 1)
            child = population[parent1][:crossover_point] + population[parent2][crossover_point:]
            if random.random() < mutation_rate:
                gene_to_mutate = random.randint(0, feature_number - 1)
                child[gene_to_mutate] = random.randint(0, X.shape[1] - 1)
            
            new_population.append(child)
            
        population = new_population

    best_idx = np.argmax(fitness_scores)
    best_individual = population[best_idx]

    best_features = np.array(best_individual)
    selected_features = X[:, best_features]
    
    tm = MultiClassTsetlinMachine(number_of_clauses=250, T=100, s=8.0)
    tm.fit(selected_features, y)
    
    return best_individual, tm

best_individual, best_tm = GA(X_train_encoded, y_train, population_size=20, num_generations=2, mutation_rate=0.15, feature_number=10, early_stopping_generations=20)

print("\nSelected Features:")
print(best_individual)

Algorithm Models¶

Random Forest, Logistic Regression, SVM and Gradient boosting classifier to comapre with my testlin machine prediction.¶

- First we implemented the algorithms¶

- then fitted it to the train and test sets¶

- then defined a evaluation metrics to make evaluation process easier.¶

-Finally, printed the output and along with the results of each model along with confusion matrix¶

Findings¶

Accuracy: Accuracy helps too know how many predictions are correct out of the tota prediction. All four algorithms have 94% accuracy, which is really good.¶

Precision: This measure helps to find the proportion of true-positive predictions. In this case Random Forset and SVM have 0 a precision value.¶

Recall: It is also somewhat linked with the True positive rates it measures the proportion if true positive predictions like precision. Random Forset, Logistic Regression and SVM have 0 a recall value.¶

F1-score: F1-score is a mean of precision and recall value its useful when we want to balance precision and recall. The F1-score was zero for Random Forset, Logistic Regression and SVM due to their precision and recall values.¶

# Defining a function to evaluate each model and print thier metrics and confusion matrix

def evaluate_model(model, X_test_encoded, y_test):
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test_encoded)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
    
    print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy}")
    print(f"Precision: {precision}")
    print(f"Recall: {recall}")
    print(f"F1-Score: {f1}")

# Confusion Matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", cbar=False)
    plt.xlabel("Predicted")
    plt.ylabel("Actual")
    plt.title("Confusion Matrix")
    plt.show()

# Evaluating models
print("Random Forest:")
evaluate_model(rf_model, X_test_encoded, y_test)

print("\nLogistic Regression:")
evaluate_model(lr_model, X_test_encoded, y_test)

print("\nSupport Vector Machine:")
evaluate_model(svm_model, X_test_encoded, y_test)

print("\nGradient Boosting:")
evaluate_model(gb_model, X_test_encoded, y_test)

Algorithm model Comparisons¶

For my project I used different machine learning algorithms in my project, the Algorithms I used are:¶

1. Tsetlin Machine¶

2. Random Forest¶

3. Logisitic Regression¶

4. SVM (Support Vector Machine)¶

5. Gradient Boosting Classifier¶

I used these algorithms to make a model that could predict if patients are at high risk of stroke or not based on their datas provided to the hospital.¶

For the tsetlin machine algorithm after performing the necessary steps and training and evaluating the model's accuracy, precision, recall F1-score and confusion matrix the findings were:¶

The model wasn't very accurate since the accuracy score is just 19.18 %, hence the model will not provide accurate predictions.¶

Precision score was 4.44% for class 1 which indicated that out of all the predictions made only a very small proportion of positive predictions were true.¶

The recall for class 1 in Tsetlin Machine was 82.61% which denotes that the Algorithm model effectively identified the true positives.¶

F1-score was just 8.43% which relatively lower, it is low due to the precision Value.¶

To ensure that the performance of Tsetlin Machine was improved we implemented Genetic Algorithm to select the most relevant features which was represented by numercial indices from the dataset. This can be used for further processes and model deployment as well. This algorithm can be also used to make predictions in the future.¶

For other Algorithm Models I used Random Forest, Logistic Regression, SVM, Gradient Boosting the process followed before making Predictions were exactly the same as Tsetlin Machine, the findings based on other algorithm models are:¶

The accuracy rate for all the other Algorithm models are very high, it was 94% for all of them, which denotes that other algorithms have higher accuracy then Tsetlin machine.¶

Precision was quite low for most algorithms, it was 0 for Random Forest, 50% for Logistic Regression, for SVM it was 0 and 33% for Gradient Boosting, which means out of all the other algorithms and Tsetlin Machine, the positive predictions made Logistic Regression was the most accurate.¶

Recall: The recall value was 0 for Random Forest, SVM and 0.011 for Logistic Regression and Gradient Boosting. In this case Tsetlin Machine is more accurate when it comes to predicting true positives.¶

F1- score is a balance between recall value and precision value, which is why it is lower for all algorithms, which was casued due to imbalance in the dataset.¶

Conclusion¶

We can conclude that in this project the algorithms needs more training to be able to make accurate predictions to actually find out if the patients are at risk of stroke or not, but since the some of the models had higher accuracy score they are able to predict that almsot accurately compared to Tsetlin Machine. Howere, in this comparative analysis, Tsetlin Machine with or without the Genetic Algorithm didn't completely stand out comapred to other algorithm models like Random Forest, Logistic Regression, SVM, Gradient Boosting. Before Model Deployement we have ensure that the Tsetlin Machine is also performs well like the other models. Feature Engineering and data balancing is also crucial to insure this step.¶

Hence, we have improve the model interpretabilty and improvement for accurate results before further processing.¶
